de.uka.ipd.sdq.beagle.core.evaluableexpressions.util

Class ModifyingEvaluableExpressionVisitor

  • java.lang.Object
    • de.uka.ipd.sdq.beagle.core.evaluableexpressions.util.ModifyingEvaluableExpressionVisitor
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    EvaluableExpressionSimplifier

    public abstract class ModifyingEvaluableExpressionVisitor
extends java.lang.Object
    A visitor allowing to create a new EvaluableExpression out of an existing one. Evaluable Expressions are immutable and can thus not simply be modified. However, it may often be wished to create a new expression out of an existing one that only differs from the initial one in some details.

    This visitor follows the same traversal strategy as RecursiveEvaluableExpressionVisitor. However, implementors may call replaceCurrentExpressionWith(EvaluableExpression) in any hook. This will replace the currently visited expression and continue traversal in the replacement. Replacing an expression will lead to a replacement of all expressions that have the replaced expression as an inner expression. These “parent” expressions will be replaced by a new expression of the same type containing the same inner expressions except for the ones that were initially replaced.

    This class offers multiple hooks for implementors. All hooks are offered for each implementation of EvaluableExpression as well as for a general EvaluableExpression, called for all implementations. The general hook will always be called before the specific one. Implementors do not have to call the super method on hooks. The following hooks are offered:

    • at: called when visiting an expression, before visiting its inner expressions.
    • after: called when leaving an expression, after visiting its inner expressions.

    This visitor will start at the expression passed to modifyRecursively(EvaluableExpression) and call the general at hook and the specific at hook. Afterwards, it will recursively visit all inner expressions and then call the general after and the specific after hook. It thus realises a depth-first traversal of the tree formed by each expression. If stopTraversal() is called, the traversal will no longer visit inner expressions. Instead, it will go “up” the tree again, whilst calling the after hooks, until it reached the initial expression and then terminate. Given that no expression is thrown,the traversal of one expression tree that only contains pairwise different inner expressions has these properties:

    • the number of all called at hooks will equal the number of all called after hooks. However, the numbers may differ for a type of specific hooks because the expression was changed during the visit. For example atSubstraction(de.uka.ipd.sdq.beagle.core.evaluableexpressions.SubtractionExpression) may be called on an expression that is replaced by an AdditionExpression in this hook. Thus afterAddition(de.uka.ipd.sdq.beagle.core.evaluableexpressions.AdditionExpression) will be called instead of afterSubstraction(de.uka.ipd.sdq.beagle.core.evaluableexpressions.SubtractionExpression) at this position when traversing upwards.
    • if for two expression e1 and e2, atExpression(e1) was called before atExpression(e2) was, afterExpression(e2) will be called before afterExpression(e1) will be called.

    Please note that evaluable expressions may often contain an instance of one evaluable expression multiple times. Replacements do however only apply to the current position in the traversal tree (and not all occurences of the currently visited expression).

    This visitor is not thread safe. It may only be used to traverse one expression at a time, meaning that its results are undefined if modifyRecursively(EvaluableExpression) is called when getTraversalDepth() does not return -1. There is however no limitation on how many expression trees can be visited by an instance of this class.

      • modifyRecursively

        protected EvaluableExpression modifyRecursively(EvaluableExpression expression)
        Starts visiting expression.
        Parameters:
        expression - The expression forming the root of the expression tree that shall be traversed. Must not be null.
        Returns:
        The modified expression. This is the expression that was build to reflect all replacements. Will be expression if no substantial call to replaceCurrentExpressionWith(EvaluableExpression) was made.

      • replaceCurrentExpressionWith

        protected void replaceCurrentExpressionWith(EvaluableExpression expression)
        Replaces the currently visited expression with expression in the expression tree. This will lead the traversal to continue in expression and all expressions for which no after hooks have been called yet to be replaced by an expression reflecting this replacement. A call to this method has no effect if expression equals the momentarily visited expression.
        Parameters:
        expression - The new expression to be inserted at the point in the expression tree at which the current expression is found. Must not be null.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - If this visitor is currently not visiting an expression tree.

      • getVisitedCount

        protected int getVisitedCount()
        Queries how many expressions have been visited during the momentary traversal. This value is only reset when starting a new visit a new expression, it can thus be used to determine how many expressions were visited after a traversal.
        Returns:
        The amount of called general at hooks since the last call of atFirstExpression(de.uka.ipd.sdq.beagle.core.evaluableexpressions.EvaluableExpression).

      • getTraversalDepth

        protected int getTraversalDepth()
        Queries how “deep” the currently visited expression is in the visited tree.
        Returns:
        how many at hooks have been called - how many after hooks have been called - 1. Will be 0 at the root expression and -1 at the before and after a traversal.

      • stopTraversal

        protected void stopTraversal()
        Stops visiting of inner expressions. As soon as this method is called, this visitor will no longer visit inner expressions. This means that only after hooks of already visited expressions will be called until the root is reached. This setting persists only until the next call of modifyRecursively(EvaluableExpression) .

      • continueTraversal

        protected void continueTraversal()
        Continues visiting of inner expressions after it has been stopped through stopTraversal(). This returns to the visitor’s default behaviour.

      • willTraverse

        protected boolean willTraverse()
        Queries whether the visitor will visit inner expressions. Will return true unless stopTraversal() is called. The value will be reset when calling modifyRecursively(EvaluableExpression).
        Returns:
        Whether inner expressions will be examined for the momentary tree.
